        <h1>LeetCode 944: Delete Columns to Make Sorted (C++)</h1>

        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                You are given an array of n strings strs, all of the same length. The strings can be arranged such that there is one on each line, making a grid. You want to delete the columns that are not sorted lexicographically. Return the number of columns that you will delete.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                Input: strs = ["cba","daf","ghi"]<br/>
                Output: 1<br/>
                Explanation: The grid looks as follows: cba, daf, ghi. Columns 0 and 2 are sorted, but column 1 is not, so you only need to delete 1 column.<br/><br/>
                Input: strs = ["a","b"]<br/>
                Output: 0<br/>
                Explanation: The grid looks as follows: a, b. Column 0 is the only column and is sorted, so you will not delete any columns.<br/><br/>
                Input: strs = ["zyx","wvu","tsr"]<br/>
                Output: 3<br/>
                Explanation: The grid looks as follows: zyx, wvu, tsr. All 3 columns are not sorted, so you will delete all 3.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    int minDeletionSize(vector&lt;string&gt;&amp; strs) {
        int rows = strs.size();
        int cols = strs[0].length();
        int deleteCount = 0;
        
        // Check each column
        for (int col = 0; col &lt; cols; col++) {
            // Check if current column is sorted
            for (int row = 1; row &lt; rows; row++) {
                if (strs[row][col] &lt; strs[row - 1][col]) {
                    deleteCount++;
                    break;
                }
            }
        }
        
        return deleteCount;
    }
};</code></pre>
